    slug: "concise-collections-of-creed-and-tauhid",
    description: `Concise Collections of Creed and Tauhid is an English-language Islamic theological work that presents the fundamental principles of Islamic creed (aqeedah) and monotheism (tauheed) in a compact, well-organized format. The book addresses the essential beliefs that every Muslim is required to hold, structured in a way that makes complex theological concepts accessible to readers without specialized training in Islamic jurisprudence or Arabic linguistics. The focus on being concise means that the author has distilled the core principles from much larger classical works on aqeedah — such as those by Imam Ibn Taymiyyah, Imam Al-Laalka'i, and other scholars of the orthodox Sunni tradition — into a format that can be studied and referenced efficiently.

The book systematically covers the three categories of tauheed that form the foundation of Islamic theology. Tauheed ar-Rububiyyah (the Oneness of Lordship) addresses the belief that Allah alone is the Creator, Sustainer, and Controller of all existence. Tauheed al-Uluhiyyah (the Oneness of Worship) establishes that all acts of worship — including prayer, supplication, sacrifice, reliance, hope, and fear — must be directed exclusively to Allah. Tauheed al-Asma was-Sifat (the Oneness of Names and Attributes) explains how Muslims affirm the names and attributes that Allah has revealed for Himself in the Quran and through the Prophet without distortion, denial, or anthropomorphism. Each section provides the relevant Quranic verses and hadith evidence that support these principles, along with brief explanations of common misunderstandings and deviations that have arisen throughout Islamic history.

Beyond the three categories of tauheed, the book addresses other essential components of Islamic creed including belief in the angels, the revealed books, the prophets and messengers, the Day of Judgment, and divine predestination (qadr). It also covers topics such as the status of the companions, the intermediate position of a Muslim who commits a major sin, the correct approach to visiting graves and seeking intercession, and the distinction between major and minor shirk (associating partners with Allah). The concise format makes this book particularly useful as a quick reference for students, teachers, and callers to Islam (duaat) who need to present clear, evidence-based explanations of Islamic beliefs. It is also valuable for Muslim parents who want to ensure their children receive a sound grounding in correct creed, for new Muslims who are learning the fundamentals of their faith, and for anyone who encounters theological questions in discussions with people of other faiths or with Muslims who hold unorthodox beliefs. The English language used is clear and precise, with Arabic terms transliterated and explained for readers unfamiliar with Islamic terminology.`,
    metaDescription: "Concise Collections of Creed and Tauhid explains Islamic aqeedah and monotheism in a compact format. Essential theology reference for students and teachers."
